<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-11-30">
  <title>Resources for 11/30</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify all <m>x</m>-intercepts of the graph of a polynomial expressed in factored form.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the factored form of a polynomial to determine how the graph of the function behaves around the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the graph of the polynomial (i.e. does the graph <q>touch</q> the <m>x</m>-axis or <q>cross</q> the <m>x</m>-axis).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given the graph of a polynomial function, derive a plausible formula for the function.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          For a quantity that depends on two variables and also has a constraint, express the quantity as a polynomial or <em>rational function</em> of one variable.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-graph-poly-repeated">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Graphing Polynomials from Repeated Roots</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on using the <em>multiplicities of roots</em> to graph a polynomial. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>Graphing Polynomials from Repeated Roots</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following problems on graphing polynomial functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              (Not on quiz) Use Desmos or a calculator to sketch <m>f(x)=2(x-1)(x-2)^k(x-3)</m> for <m>k=1,2,3,4</m>.  Do you notice any patterns?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Based on what you found in #1, sketch the graph of <m>f(x)=k(x-a)^3(x-b)^6(x-c)^2(x-d)</m>, where <m>a &lt; b &lt; c &lt; d</m> and <m>k &gt; 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Give a possible formula for the function whose graph is the following.
            </p>
            <image>
            	<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="poly-repeat">
                <diagram dimensions="(300, 300)" margins="5">
                  <definition>f(x)=-0.025*(x+3)*(x-1)*(x-5)*(x-3)^2</definition>
                  <coordinates bbox="(-5,-14,8,4)">
                      <axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" hticks="(-4,1,7)" vticks="no" vlabels="no" hlabels="(-4,1,7)" />
                      <graph function="f" />
                      <graph function="g" domain="(-1,1)" />
                      <graph function="h" domain="(1,4)" />
                      <graph function="k" domain="(-4,-1)" stroke="green" />
                      <graph function="m" domain="(-1,1)" stroke="green" />
                      <graph function="n" domain="(1,4)" stroke="green" />
                  </coordinates>
                </diagram>
              </prefigure>
            </image>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-poly-models">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Polynomial Models</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>using polynomial models in application problems</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="IZzOgiYB4o4" />

    <example>
      <title>Polynomial Models</title>
      <p>
        Find formulas for the following functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we have a box with length <m>\ell</m>, width <m>w</m>, and height <m>h</m>.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the volume of the box.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the surface area of the box.  Hint:  Find the area of each side.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Suppose the box has a square bottom and a surface area of 36 ft<m>^2</m>.  Find a formula for the volume in terms of one variable.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Suppose the box has a square bottom and has a volume of 20 ft<m>^3</m>.  Find a formula for the surface area.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we have a cylindrical can of radius <m>r</m> and height <m>h</m>.  Note that the area of a circle is given by <m>\pi r^2</m> and the circumference of a circle is given by <m>2 \pi r</m>. 
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the volume of the can.  Hint:  Find the area of the base first.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the surface area of the can:  Hint: Find the area of the top, bottom, and side of the can.  For the side, imagine what it looks like if you make a vertical cut and unroll it.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Suppose the can has a surface area of 16 in<m>^2</m>.  Find a formula for the volume.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Suppose the can has volume 20 in<m>^3</m>.  Find a formula for the surface area.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Do #1 when the box has an open top.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

